<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-285-436  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 285 436.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>InfoWorld  May 22 1989 v11 n21 p34(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Virus outbreaks spur Congress to combat threat.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Mace, Scott.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The United States Congress, stung by its own internal computervirus attack, is considering legislation to make the violation ofa computer network or local computer system a federal crime.andP;  FBIDirector William Sessions told a US Senate Committee that no lawprevents the perpetration of a computer virus that results in aloss of work time, rather than destruction of data.andP;  A new bill byRep.andP;  Wally Herger would make it a crime to cause losses or extraexpenses for its victims.andP;  H.R.andP;  55 is a successor to a similarbill introduced by Herger in the last session of Congress.andP;  Thebill has been referred to the House Judiciary Subcommittee onCrime.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Computer VirusesLegal IssuesLegislationComputer CrimesUnited States. CongressUnited States. Federal Bureau of Investigation.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>